entries.title: Microsoft tops quarterly revenue estimates on strong Azure demand
entries.snippet:
Microsoft exceeded Wall Street's revenue expectations for its fiscal fourth quarter, reporting an 18% year-over-year increase to $76.4 billion, surpassing analysts' predictions of $73.81 billion. This surge was driven by strong demand for AI tools, particularly through Azure, which saw a 39% revenue rise—beating the expected 34.75%. Azure's annual revenue exceeded $75 billion, outperforming estimates and closing the gap with Amazon Web Services' $107.56 billion in 2024.

Microsoft’s stock rose over 6% in after-hours trading, bolstered by investor optimism around Azure's role in supporting AI workloads, especially those linked to OpenAI. Despite growing competition—such as Alphabet's expanded cloud investment and capacity warnings related to AI chip shortages—Microsoft continues to innovate. It diversified its AI strategy by collaborating with companies like xAI, Meta, and Mistral, and enhancing services like Copilot and GitHub with autonomous agents.

The exclusive partnership with OpenAI is under scrutiny as the startup diversifies its infrastructure partners. To mitigate dependency, Microsoft is strengthening its Azure core services and expanding its model offerings. The broader tech sector faces pressure to deliver returns on substantial AI investments, projected to top $330 billion in 2025.

entries.title: Microsoft reports strong cloud earnings, with Windows and Xbox up too
entries.snippet:
In its Q4 fiscal 2025 earnings report, Microsoft announced strong financial results, with $76.4 billion in revenue (up 18%) and $27.2 billion in net income (up 24%). Cloud services were the primary growth driver, with Azure revenue rising 39% year-over-year, reaching $75 billion annually. Microsoft 365 also saw gains, with 18% commercial cloud growth and 20% growth in consumer cloud revenue, now totaling 89 million subscribers. 

Despite recent layoffs (9,000 positions), total employment remained steady at 228,000 employees. In the Windows division, OEM and device revenue rose 3%, while PC shipments increased 4% thanks to a Windows 11 refresh, though Surface performance remains unclear. Microsoft expects a revenue decline in OEM and devices next quarter.

Gaming revenue climbed 10% year-over-year, led by a 13% rise in Xbox content and services (including Game Pass), but Xbox hardware revenue fell 22%. Microsoft’s strategy to release Xbox titles on other platforms proved effective, positioning the company as the top publisher on both PlayStation and Xbox. 

Looking ahead, Microsoft plans to invest over $30 billion in AI infrastructure next quarter and will showcase new products at Gamescom, including the Xbox Ally handheld.

entries.title: Microsoft's Cloud Unit, Bolstered by AI Demand, Supercharges Earnings
entries.snippet:
Microsoft’s cloud computing division continues to thrive, significantly boosting the company's earnings in its fourth fiscal quarter of 2025, largely driven by growing demand for artificial intelligence (AI) services. The tech giant reported $76.4 billion in revenue, with Azure cloud services growing 39% and annual Azure revenue surpassing $75 billion for the first time. Operating income rose by 22% to $34.3 billion, and net income hit $27.2 billion ($3.65 per share), all surpassing Wall Street expectations.

The company’s embrace of AI technologies has spurred its growth and increased customer adoption of Azure for analytics and data services. Microsoft has invested heavily in AI infrastructure, with capital expenditures rising 27% year-over-year to $24.2 billion, and expects spending to exceed $30 billion next quarter. Its AI assistant, Copilot, is being integrated more deeply into Microsoft products like the Edge browser.

Despite its AI success, Microsoft has laid off roughly 15,000 employees due in part to AI automation. The company’s strong performance pushed shares up over 9% in after-hours trading, potentially raising its market value to $4 trillion. It is also in critical negotiations with OpenAI over future AI technology access and control.

entries.snippet: In 2024, Apple's position as the largest smartphone seller in China was overtaken by local competitors Vivo and Huawei. Apple experienced a significant 17% decline in its annual shipments, marking its worst performance in China since 2016. This decline has been attributed to several factors, including the lack of artificial intelligence capabilities in the latest iPhones sold in China. Apple also faces stiff competition from Huawei's premium phones and other domestic manufacturers offering innovative technologies. To counteract the sales slump, Apple has offered rare discounts and promotional campaigns. entries.title: Apple Stock Falls on Report of China iPhone Discounts. 'Winter Is Here,' Analyst Says.
entries.snippet: Apple's stock dropped by 2.8% to $243.39 on the first trading day of 2025 amid concerns over declining iPhone sales, especially in China, where the company has offered discounts to boost demand. This follows an 8% drop in iPhone sales in November, driven by a 28% decrease in China. The discounts are available from January 4 to January 7 on various models, including a 500 yuan ($68) reduction for the iPhone 16 Pro and Pro Max. entries.title: Apple shutters store in China for first time ever as struggles mount in second-largest market
entries.snippet:
Apple is closing one of its retail stores in China for the first time, signaling growing struggles in its second-largest market. The store, located in Dalian City's Parkland Mall, will shut down on August 9, 2025, due to the broader decline in consumer spending in China and the exodus of other major retailers from the mall. Despite this closure, Apple emphasized its continued commitment to the Dalian community, assuring that all staff from the store will be retained.

Apple has faced persistent challenges in the Chinese market, with falling sales for six consecutive quarters and a significant revenue drop of nearly 10% from its 2022 peak of $74.2 billion. Its smartphone market share declined from 17.9% to 15.5% last year amid increased competition from local brands like Huawei, Xiaomi, and Vivo. The Parkland Mall closure follows a broader downturn affecting the luxury sector in China, despite government efforts to stimulate spending. Nevertheless, Apple maintains a presence in Dalian through another store and plans to open a new outlet in Shenzhen, keeping its total number of Chinese stores steady at 58.

entries.title: Alphabet sees results soar, boosted once again by soaring AI and cloud demand
entries.snippet:

CEO Sundar Pichai highlighted that Google Cloud's annual revenue run-rate surpassed $50 billion, with an increase in large contracts, including several valued at over $1 billion.

Major organizations such as Wayfair, Mattel, Target, Capgemini, BBVA, and OpenAI are utilizing Google Cloud infrastructure, the latter to support ChatGPT across multiple countries. Google's AI tools also saw widespread adoption, with over nine million developers working with Gemini 2.5 and 70 million videos created using Veo 3. The Gemini App now counts 450 million monthly active users, with daily usage surging over 50% since last quarter. These achievements lifted Alphabet’s stock by 3% in after-hours trading, positioning it as the world's fifth-most valuable company with a market cap of $2.315 trillion.

entries.snippet:
Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg announced that the company is making tangible progress toward developing "superintelligence," citing that its AI systems are beginning to show signs of autonomous improvement. In a memo released ahead of Meta's quarterly earnings report, Zuckerberg emphasized the immense potential and risks tied to this advanced form of AI, noting the need for careful open-sourcing and risk mitigation. He distinguished Meta’s vision from competitors by advocating for "personal superintelligence" over productivity-focused automation.

Meta's aggressive AI expansion includes multibillion-dollar investments, talent acquisition from rival firms, and a major stake in Scale AI. The financial strategy appears to be paying off—Meta beat revenue and earnings expectations in Q2 2025 with earnings per share of $7.14 on $47.52 billion in revenue. Total costs rose to $27.07 billion, including $17.01 billion in capital expenditures. The company projects 2025 expenses to reach up to $118 billion, driven mainly by infrastructure and technical talent growth.

Though Reality Labs brought in only $370 million, Zuckerberg remains optimistic about the future of AI-powered devices like smart glasses. Advertising revenue, Meta's main income source, also grew significantly, though monetization of WhatsApp ads remains modest.

entries.title: Meta releases two Llama 4 AI models
entries.snippet: Meta has unveiled two new AI models under its Llama 4 collection: Llama 4 Scout and Llama 4 Maverick. Llama 4 Scout is a compact model designed to run on a single Nvidia H100 GPU, offering a 10-million-token context window and outperforming several competitors, including Google’s Gemma 3 and Mistral 3.1, across various benchmarks. Llama 4 Maverick is a larger model comparable in performance to OpenAI’s GPT-4o and DeepSeek-V3 in coding and reasoning tasks, while using fewer active parameters. Meta is also developing Llama 4 Behemoth, which has 288 billion active parameters and a total of 2 trillion, and claims it surpasses models like GPT-4.5 and Claude Sonnet 3.7 on STEM benchmarks. The Llama 4 series adopts a “mixture of experts” (MoE) architecture to optimize resource use. Though marketed as open-source, the Llama 4 license imposes restrictions on commercial entities with over 700 million users, prompting criticism from the Open Source Initiative. Meta’s new models are integrated into its AI assistant across platforms such as WhatsApp, Messenger, Instagram, and the web. Further developments will be discussed at Meta’s upcoming LlamaCon conference on April 29.

entries.snippet: Tesla has received its first approval from the California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC) to operate a robotaxi service. The granted transportation charter-party carrier permit (TCP) allows Tesla to manage a fleet of vehicles and transport employees via pre-arranged trips, but does not yet authorize them to provide rides to the public or operate an autonomous ride-hailing service. More permits from both the CPUC and the California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) are still needed for Tesla to launch a commercial autonomous robotaxi service. CEO Elon Musk has shifted focus to rolling out robotaxis, having recently introduced the Cybercab, a robotaxi concept without a steering wheel or control pedals. Currently, Tesla's service includes human-driven vehicles and involves friends, family of employees, and select public participants. The CPUC emphasized that Tesla must first complete a pilot program without charging passengers and follow established procedures for autonomous vehicle permits. Tesla only has DMV authorization to test self-driving cars with safety drivers and lacks approval to collect fares using autonomous vehicles. The ride-hailing service also operates in Austin, Texas, and the coverage in California includes San Francisco, San Jose, and Berkeley. The rollout reflects Tesla’s attempt to expand services amidst declining electric vehicle sales, but regulatory challenges could delay Musk’s broader goal to deploy robotaxis nationwide by the end of the year.

The company posted $1.17 billion in net income on $22.5 billion in revenue—a 12% drop from $25.5 billion year-over-year. Automotive revenues fell 16.6%, and net profits declined by 16%. Tesla also experienced a $200 million decrease in its cash reserves, with free cash flow dwindling to $100 million. Analysts warn it could turn negative by year-end. The company plans to ramp up production of lower-cost versions of the Model 3 and Model Y in late 2025 and aims to release the Tesla Semi and Cybercab in 2026. However, market confidence is waning, partly due to CEO Elon Musk's increasing political involvement and public controversies.

Falling sales, reduced regulatory credits, and the end of EV federal incentives under Trump’s budget are compounding the situation. In a bid to boost demand, Tesla has introduced aggressive pricing and financing discounts on its vehicles.

entries.title: AI could account for nearly half of datacentre power usage 'by end of year'
entries.snippet: By the end of 2025, artificial intelligence (AI) systems could account for up to 49% of total datacentre power consumption, excluding cryptocurrency mining, according to new analysis by Digiconomist founder Alex de Vries-Gao. This projection stems from estimates of energy use by chips made by Nvidia, AMD, and other manufacturers used to train and run AI models. In 2024, datacentre electricity usage totaled 415 terawatt hours, with AI possibly already responsible for 20% of that. De Vries-Gao considers factors such as data centre efficiency and cooling energy needs in his analysis. The International Energy Agency (IEA) also projects that AI could require nearly as much power by 2030 as Japan currently consumes. While hardware demand might slow due to factors like reduced interest in applications or geopolitical restrictions, sovereign AI efforts and infrastructure expansions—including OpenAI’s Stargate project—are likely to drive energy use higher. Such growth raises sustainability concerns, with datacentre reliance on fossil fuels and insufficient industry transparency. Experts, including UK’s Alan Turing Institute’s Prof Adam Sobey, stress the need for clearer data and potential AI benefits in reducing carbon emissions in other sectors.

entries.snippet: La demanda de electricidad en América del Norte está creciendo de manera crítica debido al incremento en el uso de inteligencia artificial (IA), lo que presenta desafíos significativos para la confiabilidad de la red eléctrica, advierte la North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC). El consumo de electricidad se incrementará considerablemente en los próximos años, mientras la capacidad de generación energética no sigue el mismo ritmo, situación agravada por el cierre de plantas de carbón y retrasos en la implementación de energías solares, baterías y recursos híbridos. La emergencia de centros de datos para IA y la adopción de vehículos eléctricos y bombas de calor aumentarán la demanda, llevando a un incremento del 15% en la demanda máxima de verano y 18% en invierno para la próxima década. Esta situación pone en riesgo de apagones durante picos de demanda y podría dejar la reserva energética por debajo de niveles necesarios. La generación de combustibles fósiles también disminuirá, con una reducción prevista de 115 gigavatios en la próxima década.

Here’s my concentrated, 10-year basket from the FAANG + Magnificent 7 universe (unique set: AAPL, MSFT, AMZN, GOOGL, META, NVDA, TSLA, NFLX):

**1) Microsoft (MSFT)**  
**Why:** it owns the most complete enterprise AI distribution stack (Azure + M365/Office + GitHub + Dynamics + security), and it’s already converting AI demand into revenue at hyperscale. Q4 FY25 results showed **Intelligent Cloud +26% YoY** with **Azure +39% YoY**; Azure’s annual revenue **surpassed $75B**. Management also signaled **> $30B** capex **for the very next quarter** to chase demand—evidence of durable backlog rather than hype. Cloud gross margin is compressing a bit while they build AI capacity, but at group level they still printed **$101.8B** FY25 net income and continue returning cash. Thesis is simple: sustained AI workload growth + enterprise lock-in → multi-year operating leverage from software layers (Copilots, security, data) sitting atop that capacity. citeturn2search0turn2search5turn2search4turn7search8  
**Main risks to watch:** AI ROI vs massive capex, Copilot monetization (Microsoft still limits hard paid-seat disclosures; adoption is real but early), and antitrust. Trigger to re-evaluate: two consecutive quarters of Azure growth <20% with capex still >$25B/quarter. citeturn10search6

**2) NVIDIA (NVDA)**  
**Why:** it remains the choke-point of AI compute with a full-stack moat: silicon + interconnect + networking + software (CUDA/TensorRT/NCCL) + integrated systems (GB200/NVL72). Latest quarter: **$46.7B revenue** (+56% YoY), **Data Center $41.1B**, **gross margin ~72%**, and **Blackwell** shipments ramping; management commentary and industry checks still point to demand that, in many regions, exceeds supply. The GB200 NVL72 rack-scale platform crystallizes the systems-level advantage (scale, latency, power density) that competitors struggle to match. citeturn0search1turn0search4turn0search7turn9search3  
**Main risks to watch:** hyperscaler and sovereign **custom silicon (AWS Trainium/Google TPU/Microsoft Maia)**, **AMD MI350/MI400** catching up, export controls, and **power-grid constraints** that could pace data-center buildouts. Triggers to re-evaluate: two consecutive quarters of flat/down data-center revenue while AMD/custom chips gain share, or evidence that power availability throttles deployments materially. citeturn9search0turn9news63turn11search2

financeturn13finance0

**3) Amazon (AMZN)**  
**Why:** a three-engine compounding machine—**AWS**, **Retail/Logistics**, and a fast-growing **Ads** business that throws off high-margin cash and feeds the flywheel. In Q2 ’25, AWS grew **+17.5% YoY to $30.9B**; North America retail margins kept expanding; **Advertising hit ~$15.7B** for the quarter (+22% YoY) with Prime Video ads now a real vector. AWS is also the most credible non-NVIDIA alternative in training/inference economics via **Trainium2** (Amazon’s own silicon), giving it pricing and capacity levers over a 10-year horizon. citeturn0search11turn8search1turn8search10turn9search0  
**Main risks to watch:** Azure’s faster AI pull-through, retail cyclicality, and capex intensity. Trigger to re-evaluate: AWS growth decelerates to low-teens while Azure/Google widen the gap and Ads growth slips below mid-teens.

---

## Why not the others (briefly)

- **Alphabet (GOOGL)** — Close #4 for me. Strengths: search + YouTube + Cloud (Cloud **+32% YoY**; operating margin expansion) and massive AI spend (**$75–$85B 2025 capex**). Concern: the **AI Overviews/AI Mode** transition risks cannibalizing high-margin search click-throughs while publishers/regulators push back; execution path is sound but messier. If you want a fourth name, this is it. citeturn4search2turn7search4turn4search15

- **Apple (AAPL)** — Services strength and “Apple Intelligence” could spur an upgrade cycle, but near-term **China unit softness** and staggered AI feature rollouts make the earnings bridge less clean than MSFT/AMZN. More defensive than explosive. citeturn3news19turn3search2

- **Meta (META)** — Ads engine is purring, but **Reality Labs** burns billions (Q2 loss **$4.5B**) and the metaverse/AR payoff is still unproven. WhatsApp Business is promising, just not yet at AWS-like scale. citeturn5search0turn5search6

- **Tesla (TSLA)** — Enormous optionality (FSD/robotaxi/energy), but the **robotaxi timeline remains regulatory-constrained** and auto margins have been pressured by price cuts. Great upside if autonomy truly inflects; too binary for a 3-name core. citeturn6news21

- **Netflix (NFLX)** — Ad-tier scale (≈**94M** MAUs) and strong FCF are impressive, but it’s less levered to the AI infra upcycle than the three above and remains content-cycle exposed. Solid, just not core. citeturn12news22turn12search0

---

## What would make me change my mind?

- **Macro/systemic:** AI datacenter power constraints or capital-spending indigestion that drags returns below WACC for multiple hyperscalers. citeturn11search2  
- **Company-specific:**  
  - **MSFT:** Azure growth stalls <20% YoY for 2+ quarters while capex stays elevated.  
  - **NVDA:** credible, sustained share capture by AMD/custom chips or structural supply/power bottlenecks that cap unit growth. citeturn9news63  
  - **AMZN:** AWS structurally lags competitors + Ads growth slows to low-teens.

- **Use “kill switches.”** If any trigger fires, rotate into Alphabet as the first substitute.  
- **Expect volatility.** These are AI-cycle leaders; drawdowns are a feature, not a bug.

Apple also faces stiff competition from Huawei's premium phones and other domestic manufacturers offering innovative technologies. items.title: No mention of robotaxi as Tesla launches ride-hailing in San Francisco
items.snippet: Tesla has officially launched a ride-hailing service in the San Francisco Bay Area, but CEO Elon Musk did not confirm whether the service uses self-driving vehicles. The California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC) has not granted Tesla permission to operate a robotaxi service, highlighting ongoing regulatory obstacles. Currently, Tesla's service includes human-driven vehicles and involves friends, family of employees, and select public participants. The CPUC emphasized that Tesla must first complete a pilot program without charging passengers and follow established procedures for autonomous vehicle permits. Tesla only has DMV authorization to test self-driving cars with safety drivers and lacks approval to collect fares using autonomous vehicles. The ride-hailing service also operates in Austin, Texas, and the coverage in California includes San Francisco, San Jose, and Berkeley. The rollout reflects Tesla’s attempt to expand services amidst declining electric vehicle sales, but regulatory challenges could delay Musk’s broader goal to deploy robotaxis nationwide by the end of the year.

items.title: Netflix says ad-supported service has 94 million subscribers
items.snippet: As of May 2025, Netflix reports that its advertising-supported subscription tier has reached 94 million users, a significant increase from 70 million in November, highlighting strong consumer interest in budget-friendly streaming options amid global economic uncertainty. With over 300 million global subscribers overall, Netflix continues to see robust spending across all tiers and has reassured investors that there are no significant declines in consumer streaming habits, despite concerns stemming from U.S. trade policy changes. The ad-supported plan now represents 55% of new sign-ups in countries where it is available. To further expand its global reach, Netflix enhanced language accessibility by offering more dubbing and subtitle options. This move supports the popularity of its foreign-made series such as South Korea’s "Squid Game" and Spain’s "Money Heist." However, the company faces potential challenges from a proposed 100% tariff on foreign-made films by President Donald Trump, which could affect its internationally produced content and future growth strategy.

items.title: AMD unveils AI server as OpenAI taps its newest chips
items.snippet: On June 12, 2025, AMD CEO Lisa Su unveiled the MI350 and MI400 series AI chips during the "Advancing AI" conference in San Jose, California. The MI400 series will power a new AI server named "Helios," set for release in 2026, featuring 72 chips per unit to rival Nvidia's NVL72 servers. The announcement positions AMD to compete directly with Nvidia by offering open networking standards, in contrast to Nvidia’s proprietary NVLink technology. OpenAI CEO Sam Altman joined Su onstage, announcing OpenAI will adopt AMD’s latest chips and collaborate on improving MI450 chip design. Industry leaders from Meta, Oracle, xAI, and Crusoe expressed support, with Crusoe planning to spend $400 million on AMD chips. Despite the announcement, AMD shares fell 2.2%, and analysts remain cautious about an immediate shift in market dynamics. The company has recently strengthened its AI capabilities through acquisitions, including ZT Systems and talent from Untether AI and Lamini, bolstering its competitive edge. AMD aims for strong AI chip growth despite export restrictions to China, while continuing efforts to enhance its ROCm software to rival Nvidia's CUDA.
